<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-30T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-30T06:00:00-05:00" n="494" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d494">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">860c.01/6–3045: Telegram</note>
                                <head>No. 494<lb/><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet
                                        Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HK1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss> ad interim</hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                                </opener>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#left">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                        <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                                    </seg>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-30T14:00:00+03:00">June 30, 1945—2 p.m.</date>
                                    </dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>2345. <gloss target="#t_Polco1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Polco</hi></gloss>. Sent <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> as 2345 <gloss target="#t_rptd1">rptd</gloss> London as 332; <gloss target="#t_reEmbs1">ReEmb</gloss>’s 2334, June 29,
                                        midnight.<note n="1" xml:id="d494fn1">Not printed.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                                <p>… <persName corresp="#p_BB1">Bierut</persName> in his
                                    conversation with me as reported in my 2259 June 25, 5 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d494fn2">Not printed.</note> did not raise the
                                    constitutional question in connection with the legality of the
                                    obligations of the pre-war Govt. He did indicate that he wished
                                    to scrutinize the transactions of the Govt in Exile in order to
                                    satisfy himself that they were undertaken in the interests of
                                    the Polish State. This seemed to me a reasonable attitude
                                    because of the controversies that have existed between the two
                                    groups. <persName corresp="#p_BB1">Bierut</persName> and all the
                                    Poles show the keenest desire to obtain at the earliest moment
                                    the assets of the Polish State abroad and economic assistance
                                    from the US in their vast task of reconstruction. …</p>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <persName corresp="#p_HK1">
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                                        </persName>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>